1.Preparation¶

1.1 Business Understanding¶

This dataset has over 370,000 instances of used cars and 20 features, including both categorical and numerical features. It matches the Lab requirement and is free to download at kaggle.com.

Driving is a common way to go out in the United States. US vehicle registration data shows that about 276.1 million vehicles were registered in 2018. The United States is one of the largest automobile markets around the world. In the overall US automotive market, the used car market is an important component. According to the statistics from statista.com released in March 2018, sales of new car dropped to 17.1 million vehicles while sales of used car climbed to an all-time high of 42.7 million vehicles in 2017. In the used car market, price is always a significant issue for both sellers and buyers because sellers want to sell a car at the highest price while buyers want to buy an ideal used car at the lowest price.

So we decided to use 8 different kinds of price range to help us to explore the features relationship.
(0: price < $2000; 1: $2000 < price < $5000; 2: $5000 < price < $10000; 3: $10000 < price < $15000; 4: $15000 < price < $20000; 5: $20000 < price < $25000; 6: $25000 < price < $30000; 7: $30000 < price. )

Through visualizing the features, exploring the features relationship, and other methods, we are able to help sellers and buyers to understand the most significant issues leading to the price range of used car. From the analyzing, the sellers could have an idea what kind of price range they can sell at to maximize their benefits, and the buyers could have an idea what kind of the best used car they can buy under their budgets. The end goal of analyzing a dataset like this would be to help sellers and buyers to predict the price range of car based on the different features of car they have.

We are trying to used the past data to analysis what features will affect the price range most, or which decided the car's price range. And we split our data to test whether the factors we found are really affect a used car's price range when we do prediction. If the algorithm is learning properly, we expect the difference between the actual price and the predicted price range as small as possible. This may help some websites which are helping value the used cars' price range, like Kelly Blue Book, to predict the cars' value range more accuray. That's what we are trying to achieve in this Lab.

Dataset Source: https://www.kaggle.com/orgesleka/used-cars-database

1.2.2 Classificate the price to pricerange¶

Since this time we want to do classification prediction, we need to category our price. I used 8 categories (1-8) to describe our price:
0: price < 2000;
1: 2000 < price < 5000;
2: 5000 < price < 10000;
3: 10000 < price < 15000;
4: 15000 < price < 20000;
5: 20000 < price < 25000;
6: 25000 < price < 30000;
7: 30000 < price.
Then we can drop 'price' now, since we are not going to used it now.

In [12]:
df_clean['pricerange']='0'

listBins = [0, 2000, 5000, 10000, 15000, 20000, 25000, 30000, 1000000]

listLabels = ['0','1','2','3','4','5','6','7']
df_clean['pricerange'] = pd.cut(df_clean['price'], bins=listBins, labels=listLabels, include_lowest=True)
df_clean['pricerange'] = df_clean['pricerange'].astype('int')
df_clean = df_clean.drop(['price'], 1)

The matrix graph shows the relationship between the 11 variables. (1)Price range is dependent on the vehicleType, yearOfRegistration, powerPS, model, postalCode. (2)Price is highly correlated with yearOfRegistration, powerPS. (3)The feature if it has repaired damage does not significantly affect the price (4)Fuel Type, gear Box and brand are also have negative correlations with price range. (5) As our normal understanding, kilometers have high relevant to a used car's value, however, the kilometers here shows negetive correlations with the price range. That's totally understandebal and right, because when a car's running kilometer goes up, it's price value will definetly go down, that's why the kilometers shows negetive correlations with car's price range. In this point, the price range of a car also highly depend on kilometers.

It is clear that from year 1981 to 1997, the price goes down when time goes by. After year 1997,it shows a monotone increasing relationship between price range and year. From the plot we can tell that the year of registration has high influence on the value of a used car, the year of registration more recently, the price more high. Since the used cars registrated after 2015 is not that much, we can't explain why the price range went down after 2015 based on our dataset.

From the countplot shown above, it is clear that the numbers between each pricerange are unbalanced.Pricerange 1 has the most numbers and pricerange 6 has the least numbers.After comparing with different measure models, we decided to use F1 score.Because F1 score is good at evaluating uneven cases.

F1 scores has macro average and micro average methods.A macro-average will compute the metric independently for each class and then take the average (hence treating all classes equally), whereas a micro-average will aggregate the contributions of all classes to compute the average metric. For our case, it was apparently not equally distributed, so we chose the micro-average method. And from the classification report, we can see that the micro-average methods have higher precision than the macro-average method.

3.Modeling¶

3.1 Implementation of the Multi-Layer Perceptron¶

We implemented the multi-layer perceptron based on the instructor's template code. To store all weight matrices for the multi-layer perceptron, we use a list W and do a for-loop to store all weight matrices. To implement the multi-layer perceptron, besides the _initialize__weights function, we also modified following functions: _L2 _reg, _cost, _feedforward, _get _gradient, predict, and fit. In addition, we added following functions: _phi _function, _forward _grad, _cost _grad, get _params, and set _params.

In [34]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.special import expit
import sys
import pandas as pd

# start with a simple base classifier, which can't be fit or predicted
# it only has internal classes to be used by classes that will subclass it
class MultiLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, n_layers=1,
                 C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None,
                 phi='sigmoid', cost='cross_entropy'):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden   # number of hidden units
        self.n_layers = n_layers   # number of hidden layers
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
        if phi in ['sigmoid', 'linear']:
            self.phi = phi
        else:
            raise ValueError('Invalid! This phi function has not yet been implemented.')
        
        if cost in ['quadratic', 'cross_entropy']:
            self.cost = cost
        else:
            raise ValueError('Invalid! This cost function has not yet been implemented.')
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot
    
    # Modified for multi-layer
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""        
        W = []
        
        bound = np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_ + 1))
        W_first = np.random.uniform(-bound, bound, (self.n_hidden, self.n_features_ + 1))
        W.append(W_first)
        
        for i in range(1, self.n_layers):
            bound = np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_hidden + 1))
            W_i = np.random.uniform(-bound, bound, (self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden + 1))
            W.append(W_i)
        
        bound = np.sqrt(0.5 / (self.n_hidden + self.n_output_ + 1))
        W_last = np.random.uniform(-bound, bound, (self.n_output_, self.n_hidden + 1))
        W.append(W_last)
        
        return W
    
    def _phi_function(self, z):
        if self.phi == 'sigmoid':         # implement sigmoid function
            """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
            # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
            return expit(z)
        elif self.phi == 'linear':        # implement linear function
            return z
    
    @staticmethod
    def _add_bias_unit(X, how='column'):
        """Add bias unit (column or row of 1s) to array at index 0"""
        if how == 'column':
            ones = np.ones((X.shape[0], 1))
            X_new = np.hstack((ones, X))
        elif how == 'row':
            ones = np.ones((1, X.shape[1]))
            X_new = np.vstack((ones, X))
        return X_new
    
    # Modified for multi-layer
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        result = 0
        for i in range(len(W)):
            result = result + np.mean(W[i][:, 1:] ** 2)
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(result)
        #return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2))
    
    # Modified for multi-layer
    def _cost(self, A, Y_enc, W):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        if self.cost == 'quadratic':
            cost = np.mean((Y_enc - A) ** 2)
        elif self.cost == 'cross_entropy':
            cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num(Y_enc * np.log(A) + (1 - Y_enc) * np.log(1 - A)))
            
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W)
        return cost + L2_term
In [35]:
class MultiLayerPerceptron(MultiLayerPerceptronBase):
    def _feedforward(self, X, W):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W[0]: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W[i]: Weight matrix for (i)th hidden layer -> (i+1)th hidden layer
        W[self.n_layers]: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        A : activations into layer (or output layer)
        Z : layer inputs

        """
        A_list = []
        Z_list = []
        
        A = self._add_bias_unit(X, how='column').T
        A_list.append(A)
        
        for i in range(self.n_layers):
            Z = W[i] @ A
            A = self._add_bias_unit(self._phi_function(Z), how='row')
            Z_list.append(Z)
            A_list.append(A)
        
        Z = W[self.n_layers] @ A
        A = self._phi_function(Z)
        Z_list.append(Z)
        A_list.append(A)
        
        return A_list, Z_list   # len(A_list) = len(Z_list) + 1
    
    def _forward_grad(self, A):
        if self.phi == 'sigmoid':
            return A * (1 - A)
        elif self.phi == 'linear':
            return np.ones(A.shape)
        
    def _cost_grad(self, A, Y):
        if self.cost == 'quadratic':
            return -2 * (Y - A) * self._forward_grad(A)
        elif self.cost == 'cross_entropy':
            return (A - Y)
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A_list, Z_list, Y_enc, W):
        """Compute gradient step using backpropagation"""
        # vectorized backpropagation
        grad_list = W.copy()
        V = W.copy()

        V[-1] = self._cost_grad(A_list[-1], Y_enc)
        
        grad_list[-1] = V[-1] @ A_list[-2].T
        grad_list[-1][:,1:] += W[-1][:,1:] * self.l2_C
        
        # for each instance's activations
        for i in range(-2, -self.n_layers-2, -1):
            if i == -2:
                V[i] = (self._forward_grad(A_list[i]) * (W[i+1].T @ V[i+1]))
            else:
                V[i] = (self._forward_grad(A_list[i]) * (W[i+1].T @ V[i+1][1:,:]))
                
            grad_list[i] = V[i][1:,:] @ A_list[i-1].T
            
            # regularize weights that are not bias terms
            grad_list[i][:,1:] += W[i][:,1:] * self.l2_C
        
        return grad_list
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        A_list, _ = self._feedforward(X, self.W)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A_list[-1], axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        """Learn weights from training data"""
        
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        self.gradients_ = []
        
        for i in range(len(self.W)):
            self.gradients_.append([])

        for i in range(self.epochs):
            
            if print_progress > 0 and (i + 1) % print_progress == 0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i + 1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()
                
            # feedforward all instances
            A_list, Z_list = self._feedforward(X_data, self.W)
            
            cost = self._cost(A_list[-1], Y_enc, self.W)
            self.cost_.append(cost)
            
            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            grad_list = self._get_gradient(A_list, Z_list, Y_enc, self.W)
            
            for j in range(len(self.W)):
                self.W[j] -= self.eta * grad_list[j]
                self.gradients_[j].append(abs(np.mean(grad_list[j])))
                
        return self
    
    # make the estimator compliant with sklearn's API
    def get_params(self, deep=True):
        return {'n_hidden': self.n_hidden,
                'n_layers': self.n_layers,
                'C': self.l2_C,
                'epochs': self.epochs,
                'eta': self.eta,
                'phi': self.phi,
                'cost': self.cost
               }
    
    def set_params(self, **parameters):
        for parameter, value in parameters.items():
            self.__setattr__(parameter, value)
        return self

4. Exceptional Work¶

In order to implement two more phi functions: ReLU and SiLU (also called Swish), we need to update our MLP modeling in part 3.

In [38]:
class MultiLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, n_layers=1,
                 C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None,
                 phi='sigmoid', cost='cross_entropy'):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden   # number of hidden units
        self.n_layers = n_layers   # number of hidden layers
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
        if phi in ['sigmoid', 'linear','relu','silu']:
            self.phi = phi
        else:
            raise ValueError('Invalid! This phi function has not yet been implemented.')
        
        if cost in ['quadratic', 'cross_entropy']:
            self.cost = cost
        else:
            raise ValueError('Invalid! This cost function has not yet been implemented.')
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot
    
    # Modified for multi-layer
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""        
        W = []
        
        bound = np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_ + 1))
        W_first = np.random.uniform(-bound, bound, (self.n_hidden, self.n_features_ + 1))
        W.append(W_first)
        
        for i in range(1, self.n_layers):
            bound = np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_hidden + 1))
            W_i = np.random.uniform(-bound, bound, (self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden + 1))
            W.append(W_i)
        
        bound = np.sqrt(0.5 / (self.n_hidden + self.n_output_ + 1))
        W_last = np.random.uniform(-bound, bound, (self.n_output_, self.n_hidden + 1))
        W.append(W_last)
        
        return W
    
    def _phi_function(self, z):
        if self.phi == 'sigmoid':         # implement sigmoid function
            """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
            # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
            return expit(z)
        elif self.phi == 'linear':        # implement linear function
            return z
        elif self.phi == 'relu':
            return np.maximum(0,z.copy())
        elif self.phi == 'silu':
            return z * expit(z)
    
    @staticmethod
    def _add_bias_unit(X, how='column'):
        """Add bias unit (column or row of 1s) to array at index 0"""
        if how == 'column':
            ones = np.ones((X.shape[0], 1))
            X_new = np.hstack((ones, X))
        elif how == 'row':
            ones = np.ones((1, X.shape[1]))
            X_new = np.vstack((ones, X))
        return X_new
    
    # Modified for multi-layer
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        result = 0
        for i in range(len(W)):
            result = result + np.mean(W[i][:, 1:] ** 2)
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(result)
        #return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2))
    
    # Modified for multi-layer
    def _cost(self, A, Y_enc, W):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        if self.cost == 'quadratic':
            cost = np.mean((Y_enc - A) ** 2)
        elif self.cost == 'cross_entropy':
            cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num(Y_enc * np.log(A) + (1 - Y_enc) * np.log(1 - A)))
            
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W)
        return cost + L2_term

class MultiLayerPerceptron(MultiLayerPerceptronBase):
    def _feedforward(self, X, W):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W[0]: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W[i]: Weight matrix for (i)th hidden layer -> (i+1)th hidden layer
        W[self.n_layers]: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        A : activations into layer (or output layer)
        Z : layer inputs

        """
        A_list = []
        Z_list = []
        
        A = self._add_bias_unit(X, how='column').T
        A_list.append(A)
        
        for i in range(self.n_layers):
            Z = W[i] @ A
            A = self._add_bias_unit(self._phi_function(Z), how='row')
            Z_list.append(Z)
            A_list.append(A)
        
        Z = W[self.n_layers] @ A
        A = self._phi_function(Z)
        Z_list.append(Z)
        A_list.append(A)
        
        return A_list, Z_list   # len(A_list) = len(Z_list) + 1
    
    def _forward_grad(self, A):
        if self.phi == 'sigmoid':
            return A * (1 - A)
        elif self.phi == 'linear':
            return np.ones(A.shape)
        elif self.phi == 'relu':
            return np.ones(A.shape) * (A > 0)
        elif self.phi == 'silu':
            return expit(A) + A * expit(A) * (1 - expit(A))
        
    def _cost_grad(self, A, Y):
        if self.cost == 'quadratic':
            return -2 * (Y - A) * self._forward_grad(A)
        elif self.cost == 'cross_entropy':
            return (A - Y)
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A_list, Z_list, Y_enc, W):
        """Compute gradient step using backpropagation"""
        # vectorized backpropagation
        grad_list = W.copy()
        V = W.copy()

        V[-1] = self._cost_grad(A_list[-1], Y_enc)
        
        grad_list[-1] = V[-1] @ A_list[-2].T
        grad_list[-1][:,1:] += W[-1][:,1:] * self.l2_C
        
        # for each instance's activations
        for i in range(-2, -self.n_layers-2, -1):
            if i == -2:
                V[i] = (self._forward_grad(A_list[i]) * (W[i+1].T @ V[i+1]))
            else:
                V[i] = (self._forward_grad(A_list[i]) * (W[i+1].T @ V[i+1][1:,:]))
                
            grad_list[i] = V[i][1:,:] @ A_list[i-1].T
            
            # regularize weights that are not bias terms
            grad_list[i][:,1:] += W[i][:,1:] * self.l2_C
        
        return grad_list
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        A_list, _ = self._feedforward(X, self.W)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A_list[-1], axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False):
        """Learn weights from training data"""
        
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W = self._initialize_weights()

        self.cost_ = []
        self.gradients_ = []
        
        for i in range(len(self.W)):
            self.gradients_.append([])

        for i in range(self.epochs):
            
            if print_progress > 0 and (i + 1) % print_progress == 0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i + 1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()
                
            # feedforward all instances
            A_list, Z_list = self._feedforward(X_data, self.W)
            
            cost = self._cost(A_list[-1], Y_enc, self.W)
            self.cost_.append(cost)
            
            # compute gradient via backpropagation
            grad_list = self._get_gradient(A_list, Z_list, Y_enc, self.W)
            
            for j in range(len(self.W)):
                self.W[j] -= self.eta * grad_list[j]
                self.gradients_[j].append(abs(np.mean(grad_list[j])))
                
        return self
    
    # make the estimator compliant with sklearn's API
    def get_params(self, deep=True):
        return {'n_hidden': self.n_hidden,
                'n_layers': self.n_layers,
                'C': self.l2_C,
                'epochs': self.epochs,
                'eta': self.eta,
                'phi': self.phi,
                'cost': self.cost
               }
    
    def set_params(self, **parameters):
        for parameter, value in parameters.items():
            self.__setattr__(parameter, value)
        return self

From the results in part 3, we get that when choosing sigmoid as phi function, quadratic as objective function, and 5 as the number of hidden layers gives us a relatively better result. So in exceptional work, we compare relu and silu to linear and sigmoid, set layers equal to 5, objective function equals to quadratic.
